snippet.textDisplay: I love your description of dealing with the conditions and your "private" journal. Especially, "I looked at Nikki, judged HER reaction and went off shift.."  Made me laugh and think of a particularly rough trip on a Class 40 where half our crew were completely immobilized with sea sickness. I was on deck... we just had a little too much sail up for 45kts sustained... but the foredeck was so nasty we were "biding our time" before doing a headsail change... trying to decide if I absolutely HAD to go up there. I was "privately" almost convinced the rig was going to come down in the gusts above 40+ when we'd fly into the back of the wave in front of us.... but I kept looking at my watch mate, who was the rig designer, and thinking "he doesn't seem TOO worried".  It wasn't until years later when Chris (the rig designer) and I were discussing the trip when he admitted to me that HE had been staring at ME at the same time thinking "Well, Kate doesn't seem too worried"!  Ha! I guess we were lucky we did keep the rig :)!! Loving this video, great story!

snippet.textDisplay:
"Report: U.S. the Global Leader for Reducing CO2 Emissions in 2019"
https://www.iea.org/articles/global-co2-emissions-in-2019 11 Feb 2020
The United States saw the largest decline in energy-related CO2 emissions in 2019 on a country basis – a fall of 140 Mt, or 2.9%, to 4.8 Gt. US emissions are now down almost 1 Gt from their peak in the year 2000, the largest absolute decline by any country over that period. A 15% reduction in the use of coal for power generation underpinned the decline in overall US emissions in 2019. Coal-fired power plants faced even stronger competition from natural gas-fired generation, with benchmark gas prices an average of 45% lower than 2018 levels. As a result, gas increased its share in electricity generation to a record high of 37%. Overall electricity demand declined because demand for air-conditioning and heating was lower as a result of milder summer and winter weather.

snippet.textDisplay:
Amazing adventure. This series sailing Greta and father across the Atlantic is fast becoming my favorite. I have deep affection for my home waters. I'm also deeply proud to know you have engaged this mission.

Two observations.

1. Even here on Sailing La Vagabond, I am dismayed to see the sharp uptick in downvotes involved in this journey. Take a stand for something you deeply value, and you learn who your friends are . Predicable, maybe. Still disappointing. For the record, this Yankee New Englander supports your values and your actions 110%.

2. As you learned, the North Atlantic is no joke in the winter. I follow the development and progression of weather systems in the NW Atlantic. I understand the dynamic energy between frigid continental airmasses interacting with the tropical Gulf Stream water, but am still continually astonished how fast and how ferocious the lows become during the winter months. For example, so far this winter (as of 12 Feb 2020) I have seen at least several dozen lows deeper than 940 MB riding north-eastward offshore of the states and maritime Canada. In late January I observed data from buoy 44011 (tail of Georges Banks, 170NM ese of Cape Cod) indicating 936mb pressure in sustained 60 knot sw winds...blowing with the Gulf Stream current...lucky for any unfortunate seamen in the area. Still, several of these lows have bottomed around 928-930 mb between Newfoundland and Greenland. 60+ knots, frigid freezing sea-spray, with 1000-mile fetch? Thank you. No.

[Edit] The climate model consensus predicts a North Atlantic low between Greenland and Iceland in 7 days (by 19Feb2020) that will reach 921 MB pressure...hurricane category 5 strength. The entire stretch of ocean between Greenland and Iceland will be below 935mb pressure for 5 days! Can't imagine...
